product is, has actually very fascinating

00:04:46.310 --> 00:04:54.580
story. It's called "freeki" in Arabic, modern
day Arabic, but it also appears in the Bible.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:05:01.040
If you are familiar with celebrating the holiday
of Shavu'ot, the Holiday of Weeks, in three

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:08.870
weeks, and there is a very famous love story
between Boaz and Ruth. This poor widow from,

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:14.860
from Moab, and wealthy, older man and they
fall in love and they get married and they

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:17.540
become great-grandparents of King David.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:23.630
And they're seduction scene is actually a
picnic; he's feeding her and he's feeding

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:29.370
her, in Hebrew, we say "savatla mea kehli",
any Israeli's here in the audience? Ok, you

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:35.060
remember it's "savatla mea kehli"? Pinched
her from the kehli. Kehli, in modern day Hebrew

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:42.320
means "a toast," but obviously Boaz didn't
have a toaster in the field, so it should

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:46.140
be something else. It should've been something
else, it's something that we, we call in Hebrew

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:55.590
also "karrmel" and it means green, cracked,
toasted wheat. Ok? So, why green toasted wheat?

00:05:55.590 --> 00:06:02.810
Because, in the ancient times, we have this
very, very extreme heat waves in Israel during

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:09.590
springtime and the farmers were afraid that
the harvest will be ruined, will burn out.

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:16.560
So, they harvested some of the wheat early,
toasted it so it wouldn't spoil, cracked it,

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:22.090
and used it for cooking, toasted it. So, it's
a little bit like bulgur wheat, but it's green

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:28.340
wheat. And it's extremely, extremely, flavorful.
It has some very interesting smoky flavor.

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:33.520
It's popular in Arabic and Jewish cuisine.
Actually, it's a very ancient product that

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:39.580
survived thousands of years and remained in
Arabic cuisine. And Israeli chefs just fell

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:45.460
in love with it lately and it became one of
the trendiest dishes on Israeli restaurant

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:50.651
menus. So, this shows the continuation of
tradition from the Bible all the way to the

00:06:50.651 --> 00:06:56.010
modern age and here, I think, we have --

00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:57.230
[pause]

00:06:57.230 --> 00:07:08.250
Ok, here we go. This is actually Boaz and
Ruth in the garden. And this is freeki pilaf,

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:13.940
made from one of our later, latest Israeli
cookbooks, very flavorful. I think you can

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:19.220
get it in the States as well, it's called
Green Wheat and this is the first member of

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:22.560
my Israeli dozen. And let's move on to the
next one.

00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:31.000
We're still in the Biblical times, and any
ideas what is this beautiful fruit or vegetable,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:37.440
anybody? Dates. That's right. Usually, I hope
people will say "olives" or "grapes," but

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:43.710
these are dates. Dates are one of the symbols
of ancient Israel. They are a member of the

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:48.740
seven species; the seven fruits and vegetables
with which the land of Israel is blessed.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:55.230
You all know the expression, "the land of
milk and honey." Ok, now, the theory is that

00:07:55.230 --> 00:08:00.990
the honey in the milk and honey is not bee's
honey, but date honey.

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:07.250
Date molasses, actually, and it's, it was
a very important sweetener in the ancient

00:08:07.250 --> 00:08:13.330
times. Israel was covered with date growths
that looked something like that. Ok, this

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:17.860
is the harvest. The same dates we've just
seen, the red ones, that's the way they look

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:23.050
on the tree. So, as I was saying, the date
honey, the honey in the land of milk and honey,

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:28.280
is actually date honey, and that's what it
looks like. You can see it's brown, it's sweet,

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:35.620
it's less sweet than actual honey and it's
sort of caramel flavored. And, again, it comes

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:40.780
originally from Iraq, from Iraqi Jews were
the ones who brought it to Israel because

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:45.510
you all know that Israel is actually immigrant
societies, with people coming from all over

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:48.450
the world, each one bringing their own food
traditions.

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:53.950
So, the date honey, or as we call it in Hebrew,
"silan," actually arrived with Iraqi Jews

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:59.540
and today, well, you know bee producers, honey
producers in Israel really have a problem

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:05.950
because silan is winning, becoming more popular
than actual honey. It's cheaper to produce,

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:11.580
it's less sweet, it's, and it's very, very
trendy. So, I think in the States you can

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:16.830
find it maybe in Middle Eastern shops or in
stores that carry Israeli produce. You should

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:21.371
try it, it's great for glazing. It's actually
a little bit thinner, a little bit less sweet,

00:09:21.371 --> 00:09:28.330
but it goes, again, all the way back to Biblical
tradition and yet another ingredient that

00:09:28.330 --> 00:09:32.780
comprises what we now call Israeli cuisine.

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:34.140
