Ok, and now we have something else stuffed
in the pita. Now, you must understand in,

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:30.960
in Israeli food culture, pita is not just
a pocket bread. It's a way of eating; it's

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:35.330
a way of life. You stuff anything into a pita.
You can stuff the whole lunch into a pita.

00:14:35.330 --> 00:14:40.980
You can stuff schnitzel, french fries, salad,
it goes all in a pita and it's actually sort

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:46.870
of movable, a movable lunch, moveable table.
But what we have here in the pita is actually

00:14:46.870 --> 00:14:54.670
quite interesting and unique. And it shows
for me yet another aspect of, of Israeli food

00:14:54.670 --> 00:15:00.370
culture. It is called "sabih." Anybody familiar,
except the Israelis here in the audience.

00:15:00.370 --> 00:15:03.610
Anybody familiar here with the word sabih?
Do you know what it is?

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:04.880
&gt;&gt;membermale: [inaudible]

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:10.930
&gt;&gt;Janna: Oh, ok. Good. But you know what it
comes from? What is the history? Now, this

00:15:10.930 --> 00:15:17.020
is really interesting. Sabih means "morning"
in Arabic. Sabah al khair, sabih is morning.

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:25.779
Now, it's actually combination of fried eggplants,
hard boiled eggs, hummus, which we already

00:15:25.779 --> 00:15:32.529
know, and amba, a very spicy condiment coming
from Iraq and made from unripe mango. This

00:15:32.529 --> 00:15:40.480
combination, this very delicious combo-, combination,
sandwich combo, actually originates as an

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:46.640
Iraqi Jews Shabbat breakfast. Now this needs
some explanation, I guess.

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:47.640
[laughter]

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:52.209
I guess you know that according to Israeli
religion and Judaism, you're not supposed

00:15:52.209 --> 00:15:57.740
to do any work on Saturday. Everything has
to be done in advance. You cannot light fire;

00:15:57.740 --> 00:16:03.360
you cannot do any manual work. On the other
hand, weekend is the time when you're supposed

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:09.580
to have your best meals. So, to solve this
problem, we have a lot of dishes designed

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:14.959
to be prepared in advance and enjoyed during
the Shabbat. We have very, very famous cholents,

00:16:14.959 --> 00:16:21.180
you've all heard about; the Jewish Shabbat
casserole that stays all night in the oven

00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:26.470
and then fills the house with all this hearty
smells and after you eat some, you can only

00:16:26.470 --> 00:16:31.121
go to sleep, it's so filling and so heavy.
And that's actually a good idea because it

00:16:31.121 --> 00:16:34.280
leaves nothing much to do on, on Shabbat afternoon
anyway.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:35.529
[laughter]

00:16:35.529 --> 00:16:41.830
You cannot go to movies, I mean, you know,
the observant Jews and the other thing is

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:46.411
breakfasts. Breakfasts are usually cold food
prepared in advance and thing that are, that

00:16:46.411 --> 00:16:52.230
can be enjoyed cold. Now, Iraqi Jews would
have this spread grilled eggplants, hard boiled

00:16:52.230 --> 00:16:58.330
eggs, hummus, and condiments on the table
and they would make their own pita with that.

00:16:58.330 --> 00:17:03.741
One gentleman from Giv'atayim, a small town
near Tel Aviv, turned this sandwich combo

00:17:03.741 --> 00:17:10.809
into an economic empire. He became very rich
sending this sabih thing and today can go

00:17:10.809 --> 00:17:17.970
into a trendy restaurant and all-, order a
sabih and a focaccia. But the origin is Jewish

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:23.179
ethnic tradition; Jewish ethnic food from
Iraq. And this actually teaches us two things

00:17:23.179 --> 00:17:31.369
about Israeli food. One, that it draws its
inspiration from Jewish ethnic cooking and

00:17:31.369 --> 00:17:36.539
number two, Jewish ethnic cooking is much,
much more than what we know, especially in

00:17:36.539 --> 00:17:38.119
the States as Jewish ethnic cooking.

00:17:38.119 --> 00:17:44.869
It's not just gefilte fish, chopped liver,
chicken soup, etc., it's mostly food that

00:17:44.869 --> 00:17:49.710
comes from all over the world because Jews
lived all over the world, in Iraq, in Iran,

00:17:49.710 --> 00:17:56.840
in, in Morocco, in Persia, in Syria, in Hungary,
in everywhere they lived, they created some

00:17:56.840 --> 00:18:02.500
sort of ethnic cuisine that all, at some point,
arrived in Israel. So, we sort of pick and

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:08.659
choose interesting traditions from various,
various places. I have another example here.

00:18:08.659 --> 00:18:13.869
I-, by the way, this is interpretation by
a very famous Israeli chef, Yaron Shalev;

00:18:13.869 --> 00:18:18.360
it's also called a sabih. I guess it has some
eggplants, even though we cannot see them,

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:25.590
it also has seafood and stuff. He calls it
sabih. It doesn't look like one, but it's

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:33.730
very good, actually. And here is another example,
very quick example of breakfast food of traditional

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:39.350
breakfast food. The Israelis, do you know
what it is? Jachnun. It comes from Yemen,

00:18:39.350 --> 00:18:46.909
another place where Jews lived for thousands
of years and it's actually, its dough rolled

00:18:46.909 --> 00:18:47.989
with fat.

00:18:47.989 --> 00:18:54.250
And I know it sounds sort of disgusting, no
it doesn't, you like the idea, but think about

